{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526703"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:24:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:24:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14149"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14149"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.07,0.39,0.39,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6832"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55835"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6832"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14149"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41381"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1251"},{"type":"tags","id":"1515"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2821"},{"type":"tags","id":"2988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6361"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39705"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43495"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46046"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55835"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-year history of progressive weakness in his legs and hands. He reports difficulty climbing stairs and rising from a seated position. He has also noticed trouble gripping objects and buttoning his shirts. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals weakness in the quadriceps and finger flexors bilaterally. There is mild wasting of the quadriceps muscles. Reflexes are present but diminished in the lower limbs. Sensation is intact throughout. Blood tests show a mildly elevated creatine kinase of 450 U/L (30-200). A muscle biopsy is performed, revealing endomysial inflammatory infiltrates and muscle fibres containing rimmed vacuoles.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dermatomyositis","Duchenne muscular dystrophy","Polymyositis","Inclusion body myositis","Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and investigation findings in this case are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Einclusion body myositis\u003C/strong\u003E (IBM). IBM is a rare inflammatory myopathy, affecting men more than women, with an older age onset of  around 60 years of age. It is characterised by slowly progressive muscle weakness, with potential involvement of both proximal and distal muscle groups. This patient has difficulty standing from a chair (proximal myopathy) and loss of dexterity of the hands with poor grip strength (distal muscle groups). A characteristic finding on physical examination is the weakness of distal finger flexors. The finding of sarcoplasmic \u0027rimmed\u0027 vacuoles on biopsy is unique to this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolymyositis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with symmetric proximal muscle weakness, often with a more rapid onset than seen here. While it can affect older adults, it does not have the characteristic pattern of finger flexor weakness seen in IBM.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermatomyositis\u003C/strong\u003E is similar to polymyositis but is associated with characteristic skin manifestations such as Gottron\u0027s papules and heliotrope rash, which are not present in this case. The pattern of weakness and the lack of skin involvement make dermatomyositis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuchenne muscular dystrophy\u003C/strong\u003E is an X-linked recessive disorder that typically presents in early childhood with progressive proximal muscle weakness. It would be extremely unusual for it to present in a 68-year-old man, and the pattern of weakness does not fit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmyotrophic lateral sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E (ALS) is a motor neuron disease that can present with progressive weakness. However, ALS typically involves both upper and lower motor neuron signs, often with fasciculations and hyperreflexia, which are not described in this case. The muscle biopsy findings are also not consistent with ALS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInclusion body myositis is a rare but important condition. Unfortunately it is generally resistant to immunosuppressive therapies, unlike other inflammatory myopathies. Management typically focuses on supportive care, including physical therapy and occupational therapy to maintain function and independence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Inclusion body myositis typically presents with slowly progressive weakness of the quadriceps and finger flexors.","Muscle biopsy in inclusion body myositis shows characteristic rimmed vacuoles and inflammatory infiltrates.","Inclusion body myositis is generally resistant to immunosuppressive therapies."],"references":["Naddaf E. Inclusion body myositis: Update on the diagnostic and therapeutic landscape. Frontiers in Neurology. 2022 Sep 27;13. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9551222/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41381"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14149"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41381"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T11:53:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T11:54:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6832"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55835"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t